Cumulative trading volume refers to the total trading volume of a user over a period of time, calculated by adding up the trading volume of each data point accessed by the user in chronological order; 
A data point is considered to be a single entry in the market data table, containing information such as the instrument id, date, time, and trading volume; 
The trading volume is the amount of a particular instrument that is traded during a given time period.

- "Identity" refers to the instrument's ID and name; 
- "average refined cumulative performance" and "average overall cumulative performance" refer to the average residual Winsor cumulative return and average raw Winsor cumulative return, respectively, which are measures of an instrument's performance with the Winsorization method applied; 
- "warning signals" refer to the count of alerts; 
- "raised a red flag" implies having at least one alert, indicating potential issues or notable activity with the instrument.

- Average residual cumulative return refers to the average return on investment after adjusting for external factors; 
- High and low prices represent the highest and lowest prices of the instrument during the specified time period; 
- Trading volume is the total quantity of the instrument traded during the time period; 
- User access patterns include the frequency and type (view or download) of data access, indicating user engagement with the instruments.
